Archives and compression with tar.

There are two separate ideas here that beginners often blur together, so let us keep them distinct. Archiving means bundling many files into a single stream, and on linux that is the job of tar, whose name comes from tape archive. Compression means making a stream smaller, and there are several algorithms to choose from, each with its own trade-off. Tar does the bundling; a compressor does the shrinking, and tar can call one for you.

Tar has three operations you will actually use. To create an archive you pass the create, compress, and file flags together, then the directory you want to bundle. To extract one you swap create for the extract flag. And to peek inside without unpacking, you use the list flag. The single letter that chooses the compression matches the algorithm: a small z for gzip, a small j for b-zip-two, a capital j for x-z, and a long zstandard option for z-standard. The filename convention follows along, dot tar dot g-z for gzip and so on. A nice convenience is that modern tar autodetects the compression when extracting, so you never have to specify it on the way out, only on the way in.

As for which compressor to choose: gzip is fast with a middling ratio and maximum compatibility, so it is the safe default. X-z compresses slowly but very tightly and decompresses quickly, which suits distribution packages and long-term archives. And z-standard is very fast in both directions with an excellent ratio, which is why it is becoming the modern default for new work. For everyday system-administration purposes, just know gzip and x-z, and recognise z-standard, since it now turns up in the system journal, in modern filesystems, and across recent distributions. A few flags help: dash v prints each file as it is processed, and dash capital-c changes into a given directory before working, which controls where files are read from or extracted to.
